  "text": "Animals and design. Thirty-eight crossbred (Landrance ϫ Yorkshire ϫ Hampshire ϫ Duroc) female pigs (Agricultural Headquarters, Texas Department of Criminal Justice, Huntsville, TX) weighing 12.0 Ϯ 0.3 kg (8 -10 wk) were housed in individual cages. Relatively high protein intakes are required to obtain the maximum promoting effects of pST [CITATION_1] ; therefore, animals were fed a 24% protein diet (Producers Cooperative Association, Bryan, TX) at 6% of their body wt and provided water ad libitum. Pigs were adjusted to the diet for 7 days and then randomly assigned to one of two treatment groups, either diluent (saline) or recombinant pST (gift of Dr. Frank Dunshea) at a rate of 180 g ⅐ kg body wt Ϫ1 ⅐ day Ϫ1 for 7 days. The dose of diluent or pST was divided into two daily injections (90 g/kg body wt) and administered in the shoulder region. Body weights were measured daily, and the dietary intake and treatment doses were adjusted accordingly. Pigs treated with pST were offered the diet at 6% of their body weight per day, and diluent-treated pigs were pair-fed to the intake level of the pST-treated pigs to minimize any confounding effects of differences in food intake. Daily feed allowance was divided into two meals.",
